\section{Common request handling}

The API uses two authentication mechanisms: a long-lived API key
(stored locally) and a session token obtained from the OAuth2 login flow.
The session token lives inside a [[userdata]] cookie that the server sets
after the OAuth2 callback; the API expects it in an
[[Authorization: Token]] header, not as a cookie.

We reuse the LADOK session because it already holds SSO cookies for
[[login.ug.kth.se]].
Visiting the Stay A While [[/login]] page triggers an OAuth2 flow that
completes automatically (no password prompt) when those cookies are
present.
After the redirect chain finishes, Stay A While stores a JWT inside the
[[userdata]] cookie.

We therefore keep the two layers separate.
A plain [[UGlogin]] handler remains responsible for KTH authentication
at [[login.ug.kth.se]].
A dedicated [[StayawhileLogin]] handler only understands the
Stay A While side: which endpoints use the JWT, how to read it from
[[userdata]], and how to replay a failed request with a refreshed
[[Authorization: Token]] header.

The contrast with queue endpoints matters:
the queue API uses the long-lived API key directly, while
[[/api/api_keys]] uses the browser session and JWT.
So the session object decides \emph{which} authentication style an
endpoint needs, while the two handlers cooperate on \emph{how} to renew
browser login and Stay A While session state.
<<[[StayawhileLogin]] methods>>=
SESSION_TOKEN_PATH_PREFIXES = [
  "/api/api_keys"
]

def __init__(self, base_url):
  """Create a Stay A While auth handler."""
  super().__init__()
  self.__base_url = base_url.rstrip("/")
  self.__login_trigger_url = self.__base_url + "/login"
  self.__session_token = None
  self.__rerunning_session_request = False
@

This handler deliberately ignores the KTH login page itself.
If visiting [[/login]] redirects to [[login.ug.kth.se]], an existing
[[UGlogin]] handler in the shared session should notice that and complete
the KTH login.
Our handler only claims Stay A While API responses that are missing or
using an expired JWT.
<<[[StayawhileLogin]] methods>>=
def _uses_session_token(self, url):
  return any(url.startswith(f"{self.__base_url}{path}")
             for path in self.SESSION_TOKEN_PATH_PREFIXES)


def __eq__(self, other):
  return type(self) is type(other) and self.__base_url == other.__base_url


def __hash__(self):
  return hash((type(self), self.__base_url))


def need_login(self, response):
  if (not self.__rerunning_session_request
      and response.status_code == requests.codes.forbidden
      and self._uses_session_token(response.url)):
    return True
  return False
@

The JWT is cached on the handler because the shared browser session is
already the unit of reuse for KTH authentication.
Refreshing it still starts from [[/login]], because that is the OAuth2
entry point which repopulates the [[userdata]] cookie.
<<[[StayawhileLogin]] methods>>=
def _session_token_from_cookie(self, session):
  userdata = session.cookies.get(
      "userdata", domain=urllib.parse.urlparse(self.__base_url).hostname)
  if not userdata:
    raise RuntimeError("login to Stay A While failed: no userdata cookie")
  data = json.loads(urllib.parse.unquote(userdata))
  return data["token"]


def session_token(self, session, refresh=False):
  """Return the Stay A While session token."""
  if refresh:
    self.__session_token = None
  if self.__session_token:
    return self.__session_token

  session.get(self.__login_trigger_url)
  self.__session_token = self._session_token_from_cookie(session)
  return self.__session_token


def authorization_headers(self, session, headers=None, refresh=False):
  """Return headers merged with a fresh Stay A While token."""
  merged_headers = dict(headers or {})
  merged_headers["Authorization"] = \
      f"Token {self.session_token(session, refresh=refresh)}"
  return merged_headers
@

When an API-key management call returns~403, we revisit [[/login]] so the
shared session can refresh KTH authentication if necessary, then we
refresh the JWT and replay that exact request once.
The guard [[self.__rerunning_session_request]] prevents an infinite loop
if the rerun still returns~403 for some other reason.
<<[[StayawhileLogin]] methods>>=
def login(self, session, response, args=None, kwargs=None):
  if (response.status_code == requests.codes.forbidden
      and self._uses_session_token(response.url)):
    if not args:
      return response

    session.get(self.__login_trigger_url)
    rerun_kwargs = dict(kwargs or {})
    rerun_kwargs["headers"] = self.authorization_headers(
        session,
        (kwargs or {}).get("headers"),
        refresh=True)
    self.__rerunning_session_request = True
    try:
      return session.request(*args, **rerun_kwargs)
    finally:
      self.__rerunning_session_request = False
  return response

